8 An Act relating to court reporters; amending 20 O.S.
2021, Section 106.4, as amended by Section 1, Chapter
9 100, O.S.L. 2023 and Section 106.9, as last amended
by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
10 2025, Sections 106.4 and 106.9), which relate to
court reporter duties and salaries; expanding
11 allowable means of court reporting; authorizing
certain remote availability; providing requirements
12 and authorizations for ordering transcripts;
clarifying language; updating statutory outline;
13 increasing number of certifications eligible for
certain payments; modifying continuing education
14 requirements; providing for suspension and
ineligibility for payments under certain conditions;
15 amending 20 O.S. 2021, Section 1503, which relates to
shorthand reporter examinations for certifications;
16 reducing and expanding allowable methods of shorthand
reporting; and providing an effective date.
17
18
19 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Page 1, strike the title, enacting clause and
entire bill and insert
20
21 “An Act relating to court reporters; amending 20 O.S.
2021, Sections 106.4, as amended by Section 1,
22 Chapter 100, O.S.L. 2023, and 106.9, as last amended
by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
23 2025, Sections 106.4 and 106.9), which relate to
court reporter duties and salaries; expanding
24 allowable means of court reporting; authorizing
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 1

1 certain remote availability; providing requirements
and authorizations for ordering transcripts;
2 clarifying language; increasing certain annual
salary; increasing number of certifications eligible
3 for certain payments; modifying continuing education
requirements; providing for suspension and
4 ineligibility for payments under certain conditions;
updating statutory language; amending 20 O.S. 2021,
5 Section 1503, which relates to shorthand reporter
examinations for certifications; modifying allowable
6 methods of shorthand reporting; providing an
effective date; and declaring an emergency.
7
8 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
9 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.4, as
10 amended by Section 1, Chapter 100, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp. 2025,
11 Section 106.4), is amended to read as follows:
12 Section 106.4. A. 1. The court reporter shall make a full
13 reporting by means of stenographic hand, steno-mask or, stenographic
14 machine notes, any other method of reporting authorized by the
15 Supreme Court, or a combination thereof, of all proceedings,
16 including the statements of counsel and the court and the evidence,
17 in trials and other judicial proceedings to which the court reporter
18 is assigned by the appointing judge unless excused by the judge who
19 is trying the case with the consent of the parties to the action.
20 Nothing herein contained shall be construed to authorize the
21 certification of persons as certified shorthand reporters who rely
22 exclusively upon the steno-mask for reporting judicial proceedings,
23 except as provided by law. A refusal of the court to permit or to
24 require any statement to be taken down by the court reporter or
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 2

1 tran scribed after being taken down, upon the same being shown by
2 affidavit or other direct and competent evidence, to the Supreme
3 Court, or other appellate court, shall constitute a denial of due
4 process of law. The court reporter may use an electronic instrument
5 as a supplementary device.
6 2. In any trial, hearing or proceedings, if no court reporter
7 is available to the assigned judge either remotely or in person:
8 a. the judge before whom the matter is being heard may
9 order the proceedings electronically recorded and a
10 trial or proceedings may proceed without the necessity
11 of a court reporter being present. Provided that if
12 an official transcript is ordered then it shall be
13 prepared by the official court reporter Any party may
14 order a transcript, provided that for use in any
15 subsequent trial, hearing, proceeding, or appeal, only
16 official transcripts prepared by an official court
17 reporter are permitted for any purpose, or
18 b. with approval of the judge, the parties may stipulate
19 to the use of a freelance reporter and share the cost.
20 If ordered, the transcript shall be prepared by the
21 approved reporter and shall be considered the official
22 transcript for all purposes.
23 B. 1. Upon request of either party in a civil or criminal
24 case, the reporter shall transcribe the proceedings in a trial or
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 3

1 othe r judicial proceeding, or so much thereof as may be requested by
2 the party, certify to the correctness of the transcript, and deliver
3 the same in accordance with the rules of the Supreme Court. The fee
4 for an original transcript shall be set by the Supreme Court. Two
5 copies of the original transcript shall be furnished without
6 additional charge. Each page shall be at least twenty-five lines to
7 the page and typed no fewer than nine characters to the typed inch.
8 Each page shall be no more than double spaced and the margin on the
9 left side of the page shall be no more than one and one-half (1 1/2)
10 inches and the margin on the right side of the page shall be no more
11 than one-half (1/2) inch from the edge of the paper. The format for
12 all transcripts shall be prescribed by the Supreme Court. The fees
13 for making the transcript shall be paid in the first instance by the
14 party requesting the transcript and shall be taxed as costs in the
15 suit.
16 2. When the judge on his or her own motion orders a transcript
17 of the reporter’s notes, the judge may direct the payment of charges
18 and the taxation of the charges as costs in such manner as the court
19 deems appropriate. In a criminal action, if the defendant shall
20 present to the judge an affidavit that the defendant intends in good
21 faith to take an appeal in the case and that a transcript of the
22 reporter’s notes is necessary to enable the defendant to prosecute
23 the appeal, and that he or she has not the means to pay for the
24 transcript, the court, upon finding that there is reasonable basis
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 4

1 for the averment, shall order the transcript made at the expense of
2 the district court fund. The format preparation, delivery, and
3 filing of transcripts to be used in civil and criminal appeals may
4 be regulated by the Supreme Court.
5 C. The court reporter shall file his or her records of the
6 evidence and the proceedings taken in any case with the clerk of the
7 court in which the case was tried.
8 D. To the extent that it does not substantially interfere with
9 the court reporter’s other official duties, the judge by whom a
10 reporter is employed or to whom he or she is assigned may assign a
11 reporter to secretarial or clerical duties arising out of official
12 court operations.
13 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.9, as
14 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
15 2025, Section 106.9), is amended to read as follows:
16 Section 106.9. A. Each court reporter regularly engaged by the
17 district court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of Existing Claims,
18 or the Corporation Commission shall be paid a salary pursuant to the
19 salary schedule established by the annual appropriation for the
20 district courts and Corporation Commission and in accordance with
21 the job description for the position to which appointed. For fiscal
22 year 2023 and each fiscal year thereafter, each court reporter shall
23 receive an annual salary of Fifty-three Thousand Dollars
24 ($53,000.00) Sixty-five Thousand Dollars ($65,000.00).
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 5

1 B. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
2 who are certified or licensed shorthand reporters and those acting
3 shorthand reporters pursuant to paragraph 3 of Section 106.3B of
4 this title shall be paid annually the sum of Four Hundred Dollars
5 ($400.00) for each year of service to the district court, the
6 Workers’ Compensation Court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of
7 Existing Claims and the Corporation Commission, with a maximum of
8 twenty (20) years of service only to be used for the purpose of
9 longevity, not to exceed Eight Thousand Dollars ($8,000.00) per
10 year, payable monthly. For the purpose of payment for longevity,
11 “years of service” is defined as all years served as a certified or
12 licensed court reporter in the district court, the Workers’
13 Compensation Court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of Existing
14 Claims and the Corporation Commission after June 30, 1978.
15 Longevity payments shall be made on July 1 of each year following
16 completion of the first year of service as defined herein.
17 C. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
18 eligible for longevity payments pursuant to subsection B of this
19 section shall be paid an annual equipment allowance of Three
20 Thousand Dollars ($3,000.00). Payments for such allowance shall be
21 made on July 1 of each year following completion of the first year
22 of service as defined in subsection B of this section.
23 D. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
24 who are certified shorthand reporters shall be paid the following:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 6

1 1. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
2 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds one or
3 more of the following certifications:
4 a. a Registered Professional Reporter (RPR), as
5 recognized by the State Board of Examiners of
6 Certified Shorthand Reporters. To qualify as a RPR,
7 an official court reporter shall have National Court
8 Reporters Association (NCRA),
9 b. a Certified Verbatim Reporter (CVR), as recognized by
10 the National Verbatim Reporters Association (NVRA),
11 c. a Certified Verbatim Reporter – Stenotype (CVR-S), as
12 recognized by the National Verbatim Reporters
13 Association (NVRA), or
14 d. other certifications authorized by the Supreme Court
15 that demonstrate a proficiency level in reporting
16 testimony and proceedings of a speed of not less than
17 two hundred twenty-five (225) words per minute in
18 taking a question-and-answer-type dictation, two
19 hundred (200) words per minute in taking a jury
20 charge, and one hundred eighty (180) words per minute
21 in taking literary material,. In addition, the
22 individual shall pass a the Oklahoma Written Knowledge
23 Test with a score of at least seventy percent (70%),
24 all as determined by an examination recognized by the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 7

1 Board, and shall complete thirty (30) hours of
2 continuing education per three-year cycle commencing
3 at the date of recognition as directed by the Supreme
4 Court;
5 2. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
6 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds one or
7 more of the following certifications:
8 a. a Registered Merit Reporter (RMR), as recognized by
9 the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
10 Reporters. To qualify as a RMR, an official court
11 reporter shall have National Court Reporters
12 Association (NCRA),
13 b. a Certificate of Merit (CM) or Certificate of Merit –
14 Stenotype (CM-S), as recognized by the National
15 Verbatim Reporters Association (NVRA), or
16 c. other certifications authorized by the Supreme Court
17 that demonstrate a proficiency level in reporting
18 testimony and proceedings of a speed of not less than
19 two hundred sixty (260) words per minute in taking a
20 question-and-answer-type dictation, two hundred forty
21 (240) words per minute in taking a jury charge, and
22 two hundred (200) words per minute in taking literary
23 material,. In addition, the individual shall pass a
24 the Oklahoma Written Knowledge Test with a score of at
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 8

1 least seventy percent (70%), all as determined by an
2 examination recognized by the Board, and shall
3 complete thirty (30) hours of continuing education per
4 three-year cycle commencing at the date of recognition
5 as directed by the Supreme Court;
6 3. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
7 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds a
8 certification as a Registered Diplomat Diplomate Reporter (RDR), as
9 recognized by the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
10 Reporters, and who completes thirty (30) hours of continuing
11 education per three-year cycle commencing at the date of recognition
12 National Court Reporters Association (NCRA);
13 4. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
14 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds one or
15 more of the following certifications:
16 a. a Certified Realtime Reporter (CRR), as recognized by
17 the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
18 Reporters, and who completes thirty (30) hours of
19 continuing education per three-year cycle commencing
20 at the date of recognition; National Court Reporters
21 Association (NCRA), or
22 b. a Realtime Verbatim Reporter – Master (RVR-M) or
23 Realtime Verbatim Reporter – Master – Stenotype (RVR-
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 9

1 M-S), as recognized by the National Verbatim Reporters
2 Association (NVRA);
3 5. Any official court reporter who is the holder of more than
4 one certification shall be compensated in the additional amounts
5 specified in paragraphs 1 through 4 of this subsection for each
6 certification up to a maximum of Eight Thousand Dollars ($8,000.00)
7 per year over and above the reporter’s base salary, payable monthly;
8 and
9 6. In the event of a lapse in a court reporter’s certification,
10 compensation for certification that is greater than his or her
11 salary shall be suspended until the certification is renewed or
12 reinstated. Compensation shall not be due to a court reporter for
13 any period during which his or her certification is not in good
14 standing.
15 E. Court reporters temporarily employed by the district court,
16 Workers’ Compensation Court of Existing Claims, or Corporation
17 Commission shall be compensated by the court fund of the court which
18 they serve at a rate to be set by such court. In addition, court
19 reporters temporarily employed pursuant to this subsection who are
20 required by the terms of their employment to travel outside their
21 county of residence shall receive reimbursement for mileage actually
22 and necessarily traveled to and from the place of attendance at a
23 rate not to exceed the rate of reimbursement specified in the State
24 Travel Reimbursement Act for state employees. Any travel
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 10

1 reim bursement shall be paid from the court fund of the court where
2 the service of the temporarily employed court reporter is provided.
3 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 1503, is
4 amended to read as follows:
5 Section 1503. A. Every applicant who seeks to be examined for
6 enrollment as a certified shorthand reporter shall prove to the
7 satisfaction of the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
8 Reporters that he or she:
9 1. Is of legal age;
10 2. Meets the requisite standards of ethical fitness; and
11 3. Has at least a high school education or its equivalent.
12 B. The examination for certification in one or more authorized
13 methods of shorthand reporting consists of two parts, designated
14 Part 1 and Part 2 as follows:
15 1. Part 1 consists of the test as authorized by the Supreme
16 Court consisting of the following requirements: demonstrated
17 proficiency in reporting testimony and proceedings at a speed of not
18 more than two hundred (200) words per minute in taking a question-
19 and-answer type dictation and at a speed of not more than one
20 hundred eighty (180) words per minute in taking literary materials
21 which shall be designed to test the ability of an applicant to
22 accurately prepare a transcript of testimony and proceedings that is
23 reasonably free from spelling errors. The Board may not increase or
24 decrease such minimum speed requirement, by rule or otherwise; and
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 11

1 2. Part 2 is the Oklahoma Written Knowledge test which consists
2 of not less than twenty-five multiple choice questions relating to
3 Oklahoma law and court rules, duties of certified shorthand
4 reporters, and general court procedure. The examination shall be
5 approved by the Supreme Court. A person who has tested with the
6 Board and successfully completed the written knowledge portion of
7 the examination shall be allowed to retain the credit for that
8 portion for two (2) years from the date passed, and shall not be
9 required to retake that portion during the two-year period.
10 C. An applicant who is academically dishonest when taking any
11 authorized examination is disqualified and may not take the
12 examination again until two (2) years have elapsed from the date of
13 the examination at which the applicant was disqualified.
14 D. A certification issued under this section must be for one or
15 more of the following methods of shorthand reporting:
16 1. Written shorthand;
17 2. Machine shorthand; or
18 2. Steno-mask shorthand; or
19 3. Any other method of shorthand reporting authorized by the
20 Supreme Court.
21 E. No person may engage in shorthand reporting in this state
22 unless the person is a licensed or certified shorthand reporter or
23 otherwise authorized by law or the Supreme Court.
24 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3970 Page 12

1 SECTION 5. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
2 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
3 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
4 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.”
5 Passed the Senate the 27th day of April, 2026.
